# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aide-de-camp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] An adjutant general is commander of an army's administrative services.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Adjutant comes from the Latin *adiutāns*, present participle of the verb *adiūtāre*, frequentative form of *adiuvāre* 'to help'; the Romans actually used *adiūtor* for the noun.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In various uniformed hierarchies, the term is used for a number of functions, but generally as a principal aide to a commanding officer.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] A **regimental adjutant**, **garrison adjutant** etc. is a staff officer who assists the commanding officer of a regiment, battalion or garrison in the details of regimental, garrison or similar duty.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In United States Army squadrons, the adjutant is often the officer-in-charge (OIC) of the administrative platoon.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the British Army, an adjutant (*adj*; sometimes actually referred to as this) is usually a senior captain, and sometimes a major.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] As the colonel's personal staff officer, he was once in charge of all the organisation, administration and discipline for a battalion or regiment, although now the bulk of administrative work is carried out by the regimental administrative officer (RAO).
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Until the 1970s the adjutant was also the regimental operations officer, although this job is now filled by a separate officer.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the British Army, adjutants are given field rank and as such are senior by appointment to all other captains, ranking just behind the majors.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Unlike the RAO (who is an officer of the Adjutant General's Corps), the adjutant is a member of the corps or regiment of which their unit is a part.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The adjutant's job is not solely a 'backroom' one, since he usually accompanies the colonel—Captain David Wood, the adjutant of 2 Para, was killed in action at the Battle of Goose Green, for example.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Normally, in a British Infantry battalion, the adjutant controls the battle whilst the CO commands it.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] As such, the adjutant is usually a person of significant influence within their battalion.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the Foot Guards, the adjutant of the unit in charge of Trooping the Colour is one of three officers on horseback.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In many Commonwealth armies, the adjutant performs much the same role as in the British Army.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] There is no RAO position within the Australian or Canadian armies, where an adjutant performs the administrative role with the assistance of a chief clerk, who usually has a rank of warrant officer class two.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the Canadian Armed Forces, the term adjutant is used in common with other English-speaking armies, and the corresponding French term is *Capitaine-adjudant*.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The Bangladesh Army has the appointment of adjutant which is similar to that in old British system.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Though the authorization is of captain rank, often a lieutenant can be appointed as adjutant, although a lieutenant posted as adjutant will not receive the staff pay as a captain with same appointment.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] **Resaldar Adjutant** (**RA**), or **warrant officer adjutant** (**WOA**), is a position unique to the Bangladesh Army.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] He is a warrant officer who acts as deputy to the adjutant.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In spite of this, the WOA or RA does not have any authority in official correspondences.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] His main role is the transmission and the execution of the adjutant's orders in all companies.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] On all formal parades, the standard procedure is for the squadron/company sergeant major to first report to the RA/WOA, and the RA/WOA in turn to report to the Adjutant.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The Indian Army has the position of adjutant, which is based on the old British system.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The adjutants in most cases are captains but in some cases hold the rank of major (especially in Regimental Centres).
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] **Subedar Adjutant** (**SA**) is a position unique to the Bangladesh Army and Indian Army.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] He is a subedar who acts as deputy to the adjutant.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] On all formal parades, the standard procedure is for the company havildar major to first report to the subedar adjutant, and the subedar adjutant in turn to report to the adjutant.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the British Indian Army, the equivalent position was the **jemadar adjutant**, who held the lower rank of jemadar.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The Pakistan Army has the appointment of adjutant which is similar to that in old British system.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Adjutants in the Pak Army are mostly captains and sometimes lieutenants.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The Pak Army also holds the rank of junior adjutant (JA), who works as an aide to the adjutant and is of the rank of subedar, an equivalent rank to warrant officer or sergeant in Western armies.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The regimental adjutant is also commander of regimental provost and assist commanding officer in all matters pertaining to discipline, training and operational planning.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the US Army, historically the adjutant was generally a member of the branch or regiment of the parent unit (e.g. in an infantry battalion, the adjutant was usually an infantry officer).
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In 2008, as a result of the Army's transformation, the Human Resources community implemented the Personnel Services Delivery Redesign, which recoded the adjutant position in battalions to an officer from the Adjutant General's Corps.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The adjutant general at the battalion-level is generally a junior captain or senior first lieutenant and, in conjunction with the S-1 section, manages the administrative functions of the unit.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The adjutant also works closely with the unit's command sergeant major for awards ceremonies, traditional ceremonial functions, casual events (hails and farewells), evaluation reports, and management of correspondence and other secretarial functions.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Based upon the needs of the commander, an adjutant typically from the combat arms branches may still be specially appointed in modern-day to assist a brigade commander to ease his/her burden of command.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] There is a bugle call announcing the adjutant that is still used in military ceremonies today.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the United States Marine Corps, the adjutant serves as the senior administrator for their unit, and is the OIC (officer in charge) of the S-1 or admin shop.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the French Army, Air Force and Gendarmerie, the ranks of *adjudant* (*premier maître* in the navy) and *adjudant-chef* (*maître-principal* in the navy) may be considered equivalent to Commonwealth warrant officer ranks.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] These ranks are senior to the rank of *sergeant* and junior to the rank of *major*.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Like the officers, the *adjudants* are entitled to the *mon* before their rank, as in "*mon adjudant*".
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In France, each corps has a colour (gold for most infantry units, artillery, the air force and engineers, or silver for most cavalry units, transport and materiel corps).
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] A French adjutant wears a band, with thin red line, in the opposite colour to that of his corps.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] A chief adjutant wears a band, with thin red line, in the colour of his corps.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In order to distinguish an *adjutant* from a *chief adjutant* it is necessary to know the arm's colour.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In cavalry units, *adjudants* and *adjudants-chefs* are addressed by tradition as "lieutenants".
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] Within the Netherlands Armed Forces the seniormost non-commissioned officer rank across all branches is called *adjudant-onderofficier*.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] The rank is both rated OR-8 and OR-9 within the NATO rank structure, however, it is only after 3 years as an *adjudant-onderofficier* that there is advancement to OR-9.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] An adjutant general is both a rank and a role that may represent the principal staff officer of an army; through the adjutant general, the commanding general receives communications and issues military orders.
[src:aide-de-camp/adjutant] In the United States, the adjutant general is the chief military officer of the United States National Guard units in any one of the American states.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Since the five-star grade of fleet admiral has not been used since 1946, the grade of admiral is the highest appointment an officer can achieve in the United States Navy, the United States Coast Guard, and the United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Formally, "Admiral" is always used when referring to a four-star admiral, and informally "Full Admiral", "Four-star Admiral" (or simply four-star), or "O-10" (in reference to pay grade).
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The informal terms are used to distinguish a four-star admiral from the lower-ranking admirals who may also be referred to as "Admiral".
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The United States Navy did not have any admirals until 1862, because many Americans felt the title was "too reminiscent of royalty".
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Others saw the need for ranks above captain, among them John Paul Jones, who pointed out that the Navy had to have officers who "ranked" with army generals.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] He also felt there must be ranks above captain to avoid disputes among senior captains.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Two years later, Congress authorized the appointment of a vice admiral from among the nine rear admirals: David Farragut.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Another bill allowed the President of the United States to appoint Farragut to admiral on July 25, 1866, and David Dixon Porter to vice admiral.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] When Farragut died in 1870, Porter became admiral and Stephen C.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] There was one admiral in the interim, however.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] In 1899, Congress recognized George Dewey's accomplishments during the Spanish–American War by authorizing the President to appoint him Admiral of the Navy.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] He held that rank until he died in 1917.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] In 1944, Congress approved the five-star grade of fleet admiral.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The Senate confirmed their appointments December 15, 1944.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Halsey got his fifth star in December 1945.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Nimitz (died 1966) was the last of these four fleet admirals, and no others have been appointed since.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The rear admiral got his two-inch stripe and one half-inch stripe in 1866.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The sleeve stripes had been more elaborate.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] When the rear admiral rank started in 1862 the sleeve arrangement was three stripes of three-quarter-inch lace alternating with three stripes of quarter-inch lace.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] It was some ten inches from top to bottom.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The vice admiral, of course, had even more stripes and when Farragut became admiral in 1866, he had so many stripes they reached from his cuffs almost to his elbow.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] On their dress uniforms the admirals wore bands of gold embroidery of live oak leaves and acorns.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The admirals of the 1860s wore the same number of stars on their shoulders as admirals of corresponding grades do today.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] In 1899, the navy's one admiral (Dewey) and 18 rear admirals put on the new shoulder marks, as did the other officers when wearing their white uniforms, but kept their stars instead of repeating the sleeve cuff stripes.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] During the 20th century, the ranks of the modern U.S. admiralty were firmly established.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] An oddity that did exist was that the navy did not have a one-star rank except briefly during World War II when Congress established a temporary war rank of commodore.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The one-star rank was later established permanently in 1986.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] U.S. law limits the number of four-star admirals that may be on active duty at any time.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The total number of active-duty flag officers is capped at 150 for the Navy.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] For the Army, Navy, and Air Force, no more than about 21% of the service's active-duty general or flag officers may have more than two stars, with the corresponding ratio for the Space Force being one-third, and statute sets the total number of four-star officers allowed in each service.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] This is set at 6 four-star Navy admirals.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] However, exceptions to this limit are made to meet operational needs.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] As of July 2020, there were 9 four star admirals serving on active duty with the U.S.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Some of these slots are reserved by statute.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] There are several exceptions to these limits allowing more than allotted within the statute.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] A Navy admiral serving as Chairman or Vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff does not count against the Navy's flag-officer cap.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] A Navy admiral serving in one of several joint positions does not count against his or her service's four-star limit; these positions include the commander of a unified combatant command, the commander of U.S.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Forces Korea, and the deputy commander of U.S.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] European Command but only if the commander of that command is also the Supreme Allied Commander, Europe.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Officers serving in certain intelligence positions are not counted against either limit, including the Director of the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The President may also add admirals to the Navy if they are offset by removing an equivalent number of four-stars from other services.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Finally, all statutory limits may be waived at the President's discretion during time of war or national emergency.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Four-star grades go hand-in-hand with the positions of office they are linked to, so these ranks are temporary.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Officers may only achieve four-star grade if they are appointed to positions that require the officer to hold such a rank.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Their rank expires with the expiration of their term of office, which is usually set by statute.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] For some specific positions, statute allows the President to waive those requirements for a nominee whom he deems would serve national interests.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] The nominee must be confirmed via majority vote by the Senate before the appointee can take office and thus assume the rank.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Extensions of the standard tour length can be approved, within statutory limits, by their respective service secretaries, the secretary of defense, the President, and/or Congress but these are rare, as they block other officers from being promoted.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Code can be waived in times of national emergency or war.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Admiral ranks may also be given by act of Congress but this is extremely rare.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Other than voluntary retirement, statute sets a number of mandates for retirement.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Four-star officers must retire after 40 years of service unless reappointed to grade to serve longer.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Otherwise all flag officers must retire one month after their 64th birthday.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] However, the Secretary of Defense can defer a four-star officer's retirement until the officer's 66th birthday and the President can defer it until the officer's 68th birthday.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Since there are a limited number of four-star slots available to each service, typically one officer must leave office before another can be promoted.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Maintaining a four-star rank is a game of musical chairs; once an officer vacates a position bearing that rank, they have no more than 60 days to be appointed or reappointed to a position of equal importance before they must involuntarily retire.
[src:aide-de-camp/admiral-united-states] Historically, officers leaving four-star positions were allowed to revert to their permanent two-star ranks to mark time in lesser jobs until statutory retirement, but now such officers are expected to retire immediately to avoid obstructing the promotion flow.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp-general] The Royal Air Force's equivalent appointment is air aide-de-camp, while the Royal Navy's is First and Principal Naval Aide-de-Camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp-to-the-emperor-of-japan] In Japan, the **aide-de-camp to the Emperor** (侍従武官, *jiju bukan*) is a special military official whose primary duties are to report military affairs to the Emperor and act as a close attendant (chamberlain).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp-to-the-emperor-of-japan] From 1896 through to 1945, a small number of army and naval aides-de-camp were supplied to the Emperor due to his increased status and the risks to him during wartime.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp-to-the-emperor-of-japan] Aides-de-camp to the Emperor will perform attendant duties and will relay to him military matters and orders, be present at military reviews [in his name] and accompanying him to formal ceremonies and interviews.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp-to-the-emperor-of-japan] Moreover, to the Crown Prince, the Imperial Family, and the mediatized Korean royal family (*Oukouzoku* (王公族), the former Korean imperial family), aides-de-camp were also provided.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp-to-the-emperor-of-japan] The military officers serving the *Oukouzoku* wore silver aiguillettes over their uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] An **aide-de-camp** (/ˌeɪd dɪ ˈkæmp, -ˈkɒmp/; French: [ɛd də kɑ̃]; plural: *aides-de-camp*) is a personal assistant or secretary to a person of high rank, usually a senior military, police or government officer, or to a member of a royal family or a head of state.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The term comes from a French expression meaning "helper in the military camp".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] An aide-de-camp may participate at ceremonial functions, and the first aide-de-camp is typically the foremost personal aide.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] This is not to be confused with an adjutant, who is the senior administrator of a military unit.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The badge of office for an aide-de-camp is usually the aiguillette, a braided cord in gold or other colours, worn on the shoulder of a uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Whether it is worn on the left or the right shoulder is dictated by protocol.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In some countries, aide-de-camp is considered to be a title of honour, which confers the post-nominal letters ADC or A de C.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] A controversy was raised in 2006, when president Néstor Kirchner promoted his army aide-de-camp, Lieutenant Colonel Graham, to colonel, one year ahead of his class.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Upon becoming president, Cristina Kirchner decided to have, for the first time, female officers as her aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In each of the armed forces, the chief of staff and other senior officers have their own adjutants, normally of the rank of major or lieutenant colonel, or its equivalent.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] At unit level, the unit S1 (personnel officer) doubles as the unit commander's adjutant, although in recent times in many units this practice has been left only for ceremonial purposes, while for everyday duties a senior non-commissioned officer performs the adjutant's activities.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] An aiguillette is worn on the right shoulder by aides-de-camp and adjutants as a symbol of their position, the colour of the aiguillette depending on the rank of the person they are serving (there are golden, tan, silver and red aiguillettes, as well as an olive-green one for combat uniform).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In Belgium, the Head of the King's Military Household is a two, three or four-star General who helps the King exercise the powers vested in him by the constitution in the field of defence.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] He monitors the international security situation and informs the King accordingly.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] He keeps the King posted of the situation, means and resources, functioning and missions of the Belgian Armed Forces, in close cooperation with the King's Cabinet.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The Head of the Military Household also oversees the coordination with the security detail of the Royal Palace and runs the Information Technology Service.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The Aides de Camp to the King are general or senior officers assigned by the King to accompany important visitors or to represent him on occasions when he cannot be present himself.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The Equerries to the King are at the King's constant disposal on a rotational basis; they accompany him on his travels and assist him in performing his daily tasks.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The title of honorary aide-de-camp to the king can be granted by the royal court for services rendered.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Notable people include Major General Baron Édouard Empain, Count Charles John d'Oultremont, and Lieutenant General Baron Albert du Roy de Blicquy.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In Commonwealth of Nations countries, aides-de-camp are mostly appointed from military or auxiliary services.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] They are entitled to use the letters ADC or A de C after their names.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The emblem of the office is the aiguillette worn on their uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In Australia, Australian Defence Force officers serve as aides-de-camp to specific senior appointments, such as the monarch, governor-general, state governors, chief of the Defence Force, and other specified Army, Navy and Air Force command appointments.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Honorary aides-de-camp to the governor-general or state governors are entitled to the post-nominal ADC during their appointment.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Officers of and above the ranks of rear admiral, major general, and air vice-marshal in specifically designated command appointments are entitled to an aide-de-camp with the army rank of captain (or equivalent).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Within the navy, an aide-de-camp is called a "flag lieutenant" and senior naval officers are called "flag officers".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In 1973, Sir Richard Sharples, then governor of Bermuda, and his aide-de-camp, Captain Hugh Sayers, were murdered on the grounds of Government House.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Aides-de-camp in Canada are appointed to the monarch and some members of the royal family, the governor general, lieutenant governors, and to certain other appointments (e.g., Minister of National Defence, flag and general officers, Canadian heads of mission, foreign heads of state visiting Canada).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Most aides-de-camp wear a gold-pattern aiguillette when acting in their official capacity; however, members of St.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] John Ambulance Canada wear silver aiguillettes consistent with their other accoutrements as aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] All aides-de-camp also wear the cypher or badge of the principal to whom they are appointed.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Honorary appointees to the monarch, King Charles III, or the Prince of Wales, wear the appropriate cypher on their uniform epaulette and are entitled to use the post-nominal letters ADC for the duration of their appointment.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Aides-de-camp to the governor general wear the governor general's badge, known as the crest of the arms of Canada, and aides-de-camp to a lieutenant-governor wear the lieutenant-governor's badge (the shield of the province surmounted by a crown).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] They are appointed from officers of the Canadian Forces.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Aides-de-camp to lieutenant-governors are appointed from officers of the Canadian Forces, Royal Canadian Mounted Police and, depending on the province, aides may also be appointed from other uniformed organizations such as municipal or provincial police and emergency services.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In certain instances, civilians may be appointed.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Non-uniformed civilians do not wear the aiguillette, but do wear their lieutenant-governor's badge as a symbol of their appointment.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] On 29 November 1973, Governor General Roland Michener concluded his initiative to permit aides-de-camp to the governor general and lieutenant-governors to use the post-nominal letters A de C for the duration of their appointment.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Aides-de-camp to royal and vice-regal personages wear the aiguillette on the right shoulder.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Aides-de-camp to all others wear their aiguillette on the left shoulder.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In India, officers of the rank of major general and equivalent and above in the sister services who are in command of divisions or of peacetime commands have aides-de-camp who usually belong to their general's parent regiment/battalion.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] There have been instances where the sons have served a tenure of aide-de-camp to their fathers.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In India, aide-de-camp is a title of honour, and current as well as former aides-de-camp are conferred the post-nominal letters ADC.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The service chiefs, including the chief of the Army, Navy, and Air Staff, usually have three aides-de-camp and the president of India has five aides-de-camp (three from the Army and one each from the Navy and the Air Force).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] There is also one honorary aide-de-camp from the Territorial Army.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The president may appoint any distinguished officer from the armed forces including the service chiefs as honorary aide-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The governors of the states have two aides-de-camp, one each from the Indian Armed Forces and the Indian and state police services except for the state of Jammu and Kashmir, where both the aides-de-camp to the governor are appointed from the Indian Army.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] An aide-de-camp or *adikung* as known locally in Malaysia is appointed by the federal government or the state government from officers of the Royal Malaysian Police or from the Malaysian Armed Forces officers comprising the Malaysian Army, Royal Malaysian Air Force or from Royal Malaysian Navy.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] There were also non-military or police officers who were appointed as aide-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] As in other Commonwealth countries where the monarch is head of state, personnel from the New Zealand Defence Force serve as aides-de-camp to royal and vice-regal personages.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The governor-general of New Zealand has two full-time aides-de-camp of the rank of army captain, lieutenant RNZN or RNZAF flight lieutenant.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Additional and honorary aides-de-camp to the governor-general are of the rank of lieutenant colonel or equivalent.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Aiguillettes are of the standard palace No.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Equivalent appointments also serve the minister of Defence, the chief of Defence Force and service chiefs.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] These are usually known as military assistants (MA) personal staff officers (PSOs) or, in the case of the RNZN, flag lieutenant (flags), and wear service-specific No.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] 2 aiguillettes with coloured flecks (dark blue for navy, red for army and light blue for air force) on the left shoulder.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In Pakistan, the president, prime minister, and governors have their own aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The aide-de-camp can be from any one of the three Armed Forces and typically are of the rank of captain (army), lieutenant (navy) or flight lieutenant (air force).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The aide-de-camp to Justice Khan Habibullah Khan, while he was chief minister and leader of the house of West Pakistan, was his son, a senior bureaucrat, Captain Akhtar Munir Marwat and Captain Gohar Ayub Khan was to his father, President Field Marshal Ayub Khan.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee and all the three service chiefs are authorised to have an aide-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In Pakistan, officers of the rank of major general and equivalent and above in the sister services who are in command of divisions or of peacetime commands have aides-de-camp who usually belong to their general's parent regiment/battalion.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] As in other commonwealth realms where the monarch is head of state, the governor-general of Papua New Guinea has two full-time aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] One is from the Papua New Guinea Defence Force and one from the Royal Papua New Guinea Constabulary of the ranks of PNGDF captain and RPNGC superintendent.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In Singapore, the president appoints aides-de-camp from the Singapore Armed Forces (SAF), the Singapore Police Force (SPF) and the Singapore Civil Defence Force (SCDF).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Selected SAF officers typically hold the rank of major or military expert 5, selected SCDF officers hold the rank of major, and selected SPF officers typically hold the rank of assistant superintendent of police.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Both male and female officers may serve as aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Their duties include assisting in liaison for important guests on behalf of the president and taking care of visiting foreign dignitaries.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In Sri Lanka, the president has an aide-de-camp and an extra aide-de-camp from the three armed services.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] All general, flag and air officers are entitled to an aide-de-camp, usually selected from their parent regiment or unit.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In the navy, an aide-de-camp is called a flag lieutenant.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Junior officers (of the rank of major and below) of the armed services who have completed three years of service can be appointed for (extra-regimental) special appointments as an aide-de-camp or extra aide-de-camp for a maximum of three years.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Following such appointment, reappointment is not possible for two years.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Medical officers of the rank of lieutenant colonel and above can be appointed as honorary physician to the president or honorary surgeon to the president.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The tradition dates back to the office of governor of Ceylon.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The governor's staff included an aide-de-camp as a permanent appointment drawing pay from the civil list, usually held by a retired junior officer from a British Army regiment.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] With the formation of the office of the Governor-General of Ceylon the practice continued with Ceylon Army officers replacing the British Army officers.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] At present an officer of the rank of brigadier serves as aide-de-camp to the president, while an officer of the rank of colonel or equivalent serves as aide-de-camp to the defence secretary.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The president of Tanzania has an aide-de-camp from the Tanzania People's Defence Force, with the rank of *kanali*, which is equivalent to that of a colonel.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In the United Kingdom, an aide-de-camp (ADC) was defined in 1875 as "a confidential officer attached to the 'personal' or private staff of a general".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In the field of battle, he functioned as "the bearer of his chief's written or verbal orders, and when employed as the general's mouthpiece must be implicitly obeyed".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] According to a British military dictionary dating from 1816, an ADC usually held rank equal to, or more senior than, an army captain.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] "Generals, being field marshals have four [aides-de-camp], lieutenant generals two, [and] major generals one".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The sovereign, as head of the army, was entitled to appoint "an indefinite number of aides-de-camp".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Under Queen Victoria, appointments were made (from both the regular Army and the Royal Marines) in recognition of distinguished war service; the appointment at that time carried with it promotion to the rank of full colonel.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Additional honorary appointments were made from among the officers of the Militia.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Queen Victoria also appointed a number of "naval aides-de-camp" in "compliment to the sister service".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Colonial governors, governors-general and the lord lieutenant of Ireland also appointed aides-de-camp, who had a functional role akin to that of equerries in the Royal Household in which aides-de-camp have a primarily honorific role.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] A distinctive and elaborate full dress uniform used to be worn by army aides-de-camp; however, its use was largely discontinued after World War I.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In the British Army and the RAF, a junior officer may be appointed to serve as aide-de-camp to a senior officer; the equivalent appointment in the Royal Navy is flag lieutenant.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Certain of the monarch's representatives, including lord-lieutenants of counties, may appoint their own aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In addition, a fixed number of senior officers may be appointed as aides-de-camp to the monarch, an appointment which entitles the holder to the post-nominal letters "ADC".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Most of these are serving army, navy, and air force officers, usually of colonel or brigadier rank or equivalent.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] They are seldom called upon individually to perform specific duties; collectively, they walked in procession at every coronation and state funeral of a monarch in the 20th century.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Aides-de-camp, along with equerries, military assistants, military attachés and certain other officers, are distinguished by the addition of aiguillettes to their dress uniforms; these differ in size, colour and position of wear, depending on the appointment.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In addition, aides-de-camp to the sovereign wear the monarch's royal cypher on their shoulder straps or shoulder boards in various orders of dress.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In the cases of personal aide-de-camp to the monarch and the principal aides-de-camp, the officers concerned continue to wear the royal cypher after relinquishing the appointment; and if he or she has held the appointment under more than one sovereign then the cypher of each is worn.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Otherwise, an officer would cease to wear the accoutrements after their appointment as aide-de-camp is relinquished (with the exception that former aides-de-camp to the sovereign appointed before 1988 may also continue to wear the royal cypher).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In France, the president, as commander-in-chief of the French Armed Forces, is served by aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In general, there are three, traditionally including one who is a member of the French Army, and all of whom are lieutenant colonels.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In essence, their mission is to transport the briefcase permitting the use of nuclear weapons.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] They can also provide general assistance to the president: For instance, at times aides-de-camp are seen placing the president's speech on his lectern when he arrives, or holding up cue cards for the president during award ceremonies.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] When the president travels, an aide-de-camp often rides in the front passenger seat of the presidential car.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] He is one of the people who are physically closest to the president.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The President of the Hellenic Republic as Head of State of the Hellenic Armed Forces is served by aide-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] They have the Hellenic Air Force, Hellenic Navy, and the Hellenic Army.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The Hong Kong Police Force, the Fire Services Department, the Customs and Excise Department, the Immigration Department, the Government Flying Service, the Civil Aid Service, the Hong Kong Auxiliary Police Force, the Auxiliary Medical Service, the St.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] John Ambulance Brigade, and the Correctional Services Department each sends an aide-de-camp to the territory's chief executive, which replaced the governor in 1997.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] On the last day of British rule in Hong Kong on 30 June 1997, the police aide-de-camp to Governor Chris Patten, presented Patten with the flag at Government House.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] He then gave the Vice Regal Salute before proceeding, with the Pattens, to leave Government House for the last time.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In the 18th-century, under Catherine the Great of Russia, favourites of the Empress were frequently appointed as her aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] During World War I, distinguished officers were appointed as Emperor's aide-de-camp on a rotating basis.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In November 1916, future Civil War White Army general Pyotr Wrangel (who was a regiment commander at the time) spent a few days as an aide-de-camp for Nicholas II of Russia.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] They are tasked with providing staff support and daily administrative services to the president and vice president as well as to their spouses, either in their official capacities or for personal affairs.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] They are recognized by their golden aiguillettes.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Other VIPs in Indonesia, such as ministers and other important government officials, are also provided ADCs who are usually junior-ranking officers, such as lieutenants in the military, or police inspectors from the police, who are generally newly graduated from the military and/or police academies.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] ADCs for regional officials, such as governors and Mayors, known as Regents, are provided ADCs from new graduates of the Institute of Domestic Governance (IPDN).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] There is an ADC on duty 24/7 at Áras an Uachtaráin.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Michael Collins was aide-de-camp and bodyguard to Joseph Plunkett during the Easter Rising in 1916.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] From 1896 until the end of World War II, the emperors of Japan had army and naval aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The president, as commander-in-chief of the Portuguese armed forces, is served by three aides-de-camp, one from the Portuguese Army, one from the Portuguese Navy and one from the Portuguese Air Force.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] These aides-de-camp integrate the Presidential Military Household.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Portuguese aides-de-camp never stay for more than one presidential term, which is five years in duration, after which the return to their respective branches.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In the Principality of Serbia and later in the Kingdom of Serbia, the Monarch's Aide-de-Camp held a pivotal position that bridged the monarchy and military affairs.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] This role encompassed critical responsibilities in national defence, such as advising on military strategy, overseeing the arming and training of the armed forces, and supporting diplomatic engagements.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Aides-de-Camp provided invaluable assistance to the monarchy in managing complex and sensitive state and military matters, ensuring smooth coordination with the armed forces.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Through their duties, Serbian monarch aides-de-camp embodied royal dignity, led ceremonial functions at court, and stood as enduring symbols of the monarchy’s authority and stability.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In Spain, the Royal Household has, within the King's Military Chamber or Military Staff, an undetermined number of aides-de-camp, according to Royal Decree 434/1988, of May 6, in its wording given by Royal Decree 772/2015, of August 28.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Until 2015, there were 10 aides in the service of the King, as well as an undetermined number for the Prince of Asturias.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Since the reform of August 2015, the number of assistants is not specified, although they must have the military ranks of commander or corvette captain (OF-3), lieutenant colonel or frigate captain (OF-4) or colonel or ship-of-the-line captain (OF-5).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Likewise, the requirement that the first assistant must have the rank of general (OF-6 or higher) is maintained, since he is also the head of the King's Military Chamber.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] As of 2025, the King of Spain has nine aides-de-camp at his service (not counting the first aide): four from the Army, two from the Navy, two from the Air and Space Force and one from the Civil Guard.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] These take turns 24 hours a day, every day of the year.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The Royal Thai Aide-De-Camp Department is a royal service agency under the Royal Security Command.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] It is responsible for organizing royal appearances and maintaining the safety of the Thai royal family.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Royal Thai aides-de-camp are also appointed to senior officers of the Thai Army, Navy, and Air Force.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] King Chulalongkorn initiated the Royal Guard in 1870, during his visit to Singapore and Indonesia.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] He had a lieutenant general who served as his aide, who was considered the first Thai aide-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Military officers are assigned as aides to the Secretary of the Army, Secretary of Defense, vice president, and president of the United States.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] For government officials with more than one aide, the senior-ranking aide usually coordinates the activities of the other aides as well as personal attendants such as drivers or orderlies.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The president has six military aides, one from each of the armed services.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The president's aides from the Army, Marine Corps, Air Force and Space Force are majors or lieutenant colonels, and the aides from the Navy and Coast Guard are lieutenant commanders or commanders.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] One of their major roles is to hold the presidential nuclear football.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In addition to the six permanent aides-de-camp, there are some 40–45 military social aides holding more junior ranks from lieutenant to major.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Their appointment is temporary and part-time, serving for perhaps two to four afternoons a month as required, for social purposes such as gatherings hosted at the White House.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] In the United States Army, aides-de-camp are specifically appointed to general-grade officers (NATO Code OF-6 through OF-10).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The usual tour of duty for aides is up to two years.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Although Congress has authorized general officers to be assigned up to three officer aides, their number and rank being contingent upon the general's grade, Army regulations have traditionally limited each general to a single officer aide.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Some generals are also authorized to have enlisted aides on their staff.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Lieutenant colonels and colonels in command of units (battalions and brigades, respectively) do not have aides.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Occasionally, the unit's adjutant (S1) will assist the commanding officer as an aide, but this is uncommon.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] A general of the army does not retire and remains an officer of the United States Army for life, and is entitled to an aide.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Army aides-de-camp wear a special device in place of the branch-of-service insignia, representing their affiliation with infantry, artillery, or quartermaster, that they would otherwise wear on the lapels of their service uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The rank of the general officer being served is indicated on the device worn by the aide-de-camp, as illustrated below.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Although the chief of staff of the Army and the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff are O-10 positions, their aides-de-camp wear devices specific to those offices, rather than the normal four-star aide device.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Also, an aide-de-camp wears a special aiguillette on the shoulder of their dress uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] Navy, the aide-de-camp to an admiral is also known as a "flag aide" (command ashore) or "flag lieutenant" (command afloat).
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] The highest honor of the U.S. state of Tennessee is "Colonel Aide de Camp".
[src:aide-de-camp/aide-de-camp] These colonels serve as the personal aides-de-camp to the governor of Tennessee, and their appointments are recorded by the Secretary of State of Tennessee with those who have been commissioned into the State Guard and Tennessee National Guard.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] An **aiguillette** (French: [ɛɡɥijɛt] ⓘ, from *aiguille*, "needle"), also spelled ***aguillette***, ***aiglet*** or ***aglet***, is a cord with metal tips or **lace tags**, or the decorative tip itself.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Functional or purely decorative fasteners of silk cord with metal tips were popular in the 16th and early 17th centuries, sometimes of gold set with gemstones or enameled, are generally called "aiglets", "aglets" or "points".
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In modern usage, an "aiguillette" or "axelbant" is an ornamental braided cord with decorative metal tips worn on uniforms or as part of other costumes such as academic dress, where it will denote an honour.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] This usage of "aiguillette" derives from lacing used to fasten plate armor together.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] As such, a knot or loop arrangement was used which sometimes hung from the shoulder.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] These aiguillettes should not be confused with lanyards, which are cords also worn from the shoulder (or around the neck), but do not have the pointed aiguillette tips and are usually of fibre rather than gold or silver wire, and often not braided.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The modern aglet or shoelace tip and the decorative tips on bolo ties are types of aiguillettes.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The modern aiguillette derives from the laces used to secure plates of armor together.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The breast- and back-plates would be attached on one side with short loops of cord acting as a hinge, and on the other by a longer and more ornate tied one, to support the arm defences.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Another tradition traces a symbolic use of a Aiguillettes to Spain, after the Duke of Alba condemned deserting Flemish to face the rope.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The Flemish decided to wear a cord and a nail on their collar as a symbol of their defiance.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The cord and the nail came seen as an emblem of their bravery and ultimately became the honour known as aiguillettes.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Portraits of the 16th and 17th centuries show that aiglets or metal tips could be functional or purely decorative, though many were used to "close" seams and slashes that are not always apparent on dark garments in portraits.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] They were made in matched sets, might be of silver, silver-gilt, or gold, and were worn in masses.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A 1547 inventory of Henry VIII of England's wardrobe includes one coat with 12 pairs of aiglets, and 11 gowns with a total of 367 pairs.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The *Day Book of the Wardrobe of Robes* of Elizabeth I records items received into storage, including details of buttons and aiglets lost from the Queen's clothing.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Elizabeth's aiglets were variously enameled with white, red, black, blue, and purple details or set with diamonds, garnets, rubies and pearls.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In Scotland, they were known as "horns", Mary, Queen of Scots had pairs of gold horns enamelled in red and white and set with pearls.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Those of Anne of Denmark in the early years of the 17th century were larger, shaped in triangles and pyramids.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] One set of 24 were made three-sided, with "27 diamonds in the sides and one in the top", for a total of 642 diamonds in the set.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes are worn on the right shoulder by armed forces officers serving in specific positions, such as aide-de-camp to the President, the Minister of Defense, each service's chief of staff and unit commanding officers, and by military attachés to Argentinian embassies abroad.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The color of the aiguillette may be golden, silver or tan, depending the nature of the assignment.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Olive green aiguillettes are worn with the combat uniform in very special circumstances, such as ceremonies and inspections.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Otherwise, aiguillettes are not worn with the combat uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A special red aiguillette is worn by the adjutants to the commanding officers of the Horse Grenadiers Regiment (the presidential guard) and the Military Academy.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Also, a red aiguillette is worn on the left shoulder by the senior NCO of each Army unit.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A thinner, yellow aiguillette is worn on the right shoulder by NCOs who have completed the instructor course.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In the Navy, adjutants to very senior officers wear golden aiguillettes on the left shoulder.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes distinguish officers of Flag, General and Air rank in specific command appointments, military attachés and aides-de-camp.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Most senior officers and aides-de-camp to the Governor-General or state governors wear the aiguillette on the right shoulder, whilst military attachés and staff aides-de-camp wear the aiguillette on the left.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Royal aiguillettes are of plain gold, naval aiguillettes are of blue and gold, army aiguillettes are of red and gold, air force aiguillettes of light blue and gold.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The Governor-General of Australia, as the Commander in Chief of the Australian Defence Force, is entitled to wear a uniform on which an aiguillette made of platinum is worn.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes are worn by officers in specific appointments to specific principals.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] For all regal and vice-regal appointments, the distinguishing badge or cipher of the principal is worn on the shoulder strap or shoulder board.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Obsolete pattern aiguillettes braided with a coloured stripe may be worn until replaced by officers holding appointments to Lieutenant-Governors of provinces or military / civilian principals.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] For RCAF officers, since the uniform jacket does not normally include shoulder straps, there is a small attachment hook worn on the appropriate shoulder to which the aiguillette is fastened.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] For Army officers, the aiguillette is secured under the appropriate shoulder strap (left or right) and the cipher or badge (if appropriate) is worn on that shoulder strap.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] For all branches, the end of the cord near the hanging ends is fastened to a concealed button under the left or right jacket lapel as appropriate.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The Danish military uses aiguillettes for a number of different positions.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The aiguillettes are worn only with the dress uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes should not be confused with *fourragères*, which can be worn in the same way on the left shoulder in parade dress.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In the German armies, including the Imperial German Army and the Imperial German Navy, the adjutant generals or admirals wore the *Adjutantenschnur* or *Achselband* (adjutant cord or aguilette) on the right shoulder as of 1863 in gold, the generals *à la suite* and the *Flügeladjutanten* in silver.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] There were initially several experimental forms in the Reichswehr.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] On 29 June 1935, so-called shoulder straps were introduced into the German Wehrmacht and were worn on certain occasions, e.g. at parades.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Adjutants wore armpit cords as their badge of activity.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In the Bundeswehr it is worn by attachés, officers of protocol, flag escort officers, greeting and liaison officers of the Navy as well as (if these tasks are carried out by officers) wake guards and medal cushion bearers.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In Ghana, aiguillettes form part of the ceremonial uniforms of commissioned officers in the army and other security services including the police, prisons service, fire service, and customs and immigration.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Senior police officers wear white aiguillettes with dark-blue uniforms, prison officers also wear yellow aiguillettes over the official ceremonial number one uniform while customs and immigration officials wear red aiguillettes with olive-green outfits.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] When worn, the aiguillettes denote on-duty status.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes are worn by the aides-de-camp to the President of the Hellenic Republic.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The President's Adjutants wears it on the right shoulder.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes are worn by the aides-de-camp to the President and Taoiseach.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The President's ADC wears it on the right shoulder, the Taoiseach's ADC on the left.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Civil Defence (Cosaint Sibhialta) personnel wear a white aiguillette on their dress uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Gold aiguillettes are also worn by officers in the Defence Forces with their mess dress uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] They are worn on the left hand shoulder.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In the IDF, soldiers who wear an aiguillette are mostly instructors.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In the Israeli Police, policemen mainly wear a black aiguillette, and Israeli Border Police policemen wear a dark green aiguillette.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes are worn by honor guard personnel.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A single silver aiguillette is worn on enlisted cut uniforms of minor detachments.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A single gold aiguillette is worn on officer cut uniforms of minor detachments.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A double gold aiguillette is worn on officer cut uniforms of major detachments.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] All personnel of major detachments wear officer cut uniforms.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Demobilized soldiers also often decorate their uniforms with makeshift aiguillettes.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes are worn on the right shoulder by officers of certain appointments only.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes are also worn on the left shoulder by musicians of the Singapore Armed Forces Band and the Singapore Police Force Band.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Musicians of the Singapore Armed Forces Band wears a red and gold aiguillette while Director of Musics of the Singapore Armed Forces Band wear a full gold aiguillette.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Student musicians from both the National Cadet Corps Command Band and National Police Cadet Corps Band similarly wear aiguillettes mirroring the respective parent bodies.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In Singapore, ADCs who are officers of the Singapore Armed Forces and the Singapore Civil Defence Force wear gold aiguillettes and police officers wear silver aiguillettes.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Singapore Armed Forces ADCs wear a gold braid lanyard in lieu of an aiguillette when in No.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Additionally the newly commissioned ADC badges are worn across all five services' no.4 uniform.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In Sri Lanka, full aiguillettes are worn by members of the personal staff of the President of Sri Lanka and General officers, flag officers and air officers, while half aiguillettes are worn by the Colonels and Lieutenant Colonels in ceremonial uniforms.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In the Sri Lanka Police, the Inspector General of Police, wear gold aiguillettes on the right shoulder, while Senior gazetted police officers wear black aiguillettes on the left shoulder in both formal and ceremonial dress.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The Swedish Armed Forces uses three types of aiguillettes.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] All aiguillettes come in gold or silver braid depending on the regiment of the wearer, Royal Guard regiments use silver due to historical reasons, all others gold.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In Sweden there is a distinction between the aiguillettes mentioned above, and other cords used on uniforms in the Royal Swedish Navy and the Swedish Air Force.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] There are four types of aiguillette worn by the British Armed Forces.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Aiguillettes are also worn by some police officers.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The aiguillette is worn on the right shoulder by military aides to the President and the Vice President.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The gold cord aiguillette is worn by the directors of the United States Marine Band, while the enlisted personnel wear aiguillettes of white cord.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A red aiguillette is worn on the left shoulder by United States Navy Recruit Division commanders, whereas a blue aiguillette is worn by Recruit Division commanders in training.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Recruit Division commanders wearing these are referred colloquially as "red ropes" and "blue ropes" respectively.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Navy Ceremonial Guard in Washington, D.C. wears a blue aiguillette on summer white uniforms and a white one on winter blue uniforms.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] From 1983 until the issue of the campaign hat, Women Marine Drill Instructors wore a red aiguillette similar to the Navy.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A blue aiguillette is worn on the left shoulder by military training leaders at technical training bases.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Students wearing a white rope are commonly referred to as chapel guides, and are charged with providing social or moral support to their fellow airmen.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Airmen who wear the black rope are experts in drill, choir, or ceremonies, and pride themselves on appearance and uniform wear.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Airmen who wear a blue and white rope are members of the drum & bugle corps for their base.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] In the United States Air Force, honor guard members wear a silver aiguillette on the left shoulder.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] The aiguillette should not be confused with the fourragère, which is used by a number of European militaries as well as by some United States units awarded decorations in the First and Second World Wars.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Nor should it be confused with the Schützenschnur, a multi-weapon marksmanship decoration awarded by Germany to qualifying soldiers of NATO countries serving in Germany.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] A similar, albeit thicker, device, the Infantry Shoulder Cord, is worn on the right shoulder by all enlisted soldiers and officers in the United States Army whose primary Military Occupational Specialty is infantry.
[src:aide-de-camp/aiguillette] Many military units wear dress lanyards.
[src:aide-de-camp/air-aide-de-camp] An **air aide-de-camp** is a senior honorary aide-de-camp appointment for air officers in the Royal Air Force, the Royal Australian Air Force and the Indian Air Force.
[src:aide-de-camp/air-aide-de-camp] Normally the recipient is appointed as an air aide-de-camp to the head of state.
[src:aide-de-camp/air-aide-de-camp] The British Army's equivalent appointment is aide-de-camp general.
